body:
## Bug Description
An example: 
`main.cpp`:
```c++
#include "VTop.h"
#include "verilated.h"

int main() {
        VerilatedContext* contextp = new VerilatedContext;
        VTop* top = new VTop{contextp};
        top->clock = 0;
        top->index = 0;
        top->eval();
        top->clock = 1;
        top->eval();
        for (int i = 0; i <= 7; i++) {
                printf("i is %d,", i);
                top->clock = 0;
                top->index = i;
                top->eval();
                top->clock = 1;
                top->eval();
                printf("Res is %x\n", top->out);
        }
        top->final();
        delete top;
}
```

`Top.v`:
```verilog
module Top(
        input clock,
        input [2:0] index,
        output [27:0] out
        );
        reg [27:0] res;

        wire [2:0] flipped_index = ~index;
        always @(posedge clock) begin
                automatic logic [7:0][26:0] array = {27'h33, 27'h34, 27'h35, 27'h36, 27'h37, 27'h38, 27'h39, 27'h40};
                res <= array[~flipped_index];
        end

        assign out = res;
endmodule
```

Build command: `verilator -Wall -Wno-WIDTH --cc -O0 --exe --build main.cpp Top.v`

It seems that 2 factors are necessary to trigger this bug: 
- the width of array elements should not be power of 2 (eg. 32)
- the index must be flipped when accessing the array

## Verilator version:
Verilator 4.221 devel rev v4.220-21-g5f333be9 (mod)

## OS:
Arch Linux with verilator master and Ubuntu 20.04LTS with verilator 4.218
